A design for a differential drive robot is proposed, featuring a cost-effective Bill of Materials (BoM) with high capabilities. All components are powered by a 2S 25C LiPo
battery. Overall control of the processes is managed by an ESP32 Wroom MCU. Three DC motors with different reduction gears are used for traction and operation of the
robot. A DC motor driver is employed to control the direction and speed of rotation using PWM signals. The differential drive system enables fast and tight turns with
minimal mechanical losses. A servomotor is attached to a four-bar linkage designed to lift opponents. This linkage is configured with the Chebyshev Lambda-proposed
lengths to ensure approximate straight-line motion.
